o on modern political history.Laks shows how the four central ideas in the Laws—the corruptibility of unchecked power, the rule of law, a “middle” constitution, and the political necessity of legislative preambles—are articulated within an intricate and masterful literary architecture. He reveals how the work develops a theological conception of law anchored in political ideas about a god, divine reason, that is the measure of political order. Laks’s reading opens a complex analysis of the relationships between rulers and citizens; their roles in a political system; the power of reason and persuasion, as opposed to force, in commanding obedience; and the place of freedom.Beyond the Republic presents a sophisticated reevaluation of a philosophical work that has exerted an enormous if often hidden influence even into the present day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAdornment.  aAeschylus.  aAgainst Apion.  aAnalogy.  aAnalytics.  aAristotle.  aAssonance.  aBonus Bill of 1817.  aBook.  aCardinal virtues.  aCircumlocution.  aClause.  aCoaching.  aConcave function.  aCondition of possibility.  aConsideration.  aConstitutionalism.  aCorruption.  aCowardice.  aCriticism.  aCritique of Pure Reason.  aCritique.  aDeliberation.  aDemiurge.  aDespotism.  aElectoral college.  aEssay.  aExplanation.  aFamily resemblance.  aFeeling.  aGlaucon.  aHamartia.  aHeteronomy.  aHypothesis.  aImpossibility.  aImpracticability.  aInstant-runoff voting.  aInvoluntary servitude.  aIpso facto.  aIrony.  aIrrationality.  aKrater.  aLawgiver (Judge Dredd).  aLegislation.  aLetter of resignation.  aNecessity.  aNetwork theory.  aNew Laws.  aNomos (sociology).  aNoocracy.  aNous.  aO